column168: Our driver showed plant personnel our paperwork that identified the product being delivered and the quantity of the same.  The plant operator signed our disclaimer indicating that we were hooked to the correct line to deliver and assured our driver that their storage tank was capable of holding all of the product.  During the unloading process, our driver heard a noise and investigated finding that one of the storage tanks was over flowing with product so he closed the discharge valves on our trailer.  Product overflow stopped shortly thereafter.      The plant's was expecting a delivery much less than what was shipped on our tank.  All of the spilled product was contained in levy around the storage tanks so no drains were affected.
column169: High level product alarms or having someone at the delivery point to monitor the tank receiving the product level gauge if any should prevent this type of occurrence.

column168: During a routine hazardous materials and safety inspection at CR's Frankford Junction Yard, Philadelphia, PA, Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) Inspector R.L. Ingram, SR, noted a hissing sound and odor of product coming from the area of the manway cover on tank car TILX 280687, containing the residue of Acetone.  Mr. Ingram reported his finding to CR Trainmaster L. Stinger, who in turn contacted CR's A.W. Richter, Manager Risk Mgmt.  Mr. Richter contacted CHEMTREC, who in turn notified both the shipper (Eastman Chemical, Kingsport, TN) and Consignee (Sunoco, Inc., Philadelphia, PA; Frankford Junction Yard is serving yard for this Sunoco consignee).  Sunoco had Union Tank Car (UTC) Mobil Unit respond. UTC found all 6 manway cover securement bolts adequately tight, but were able to gain another 1/2 turn on all bolts.  Hissing ceased.  Car okayed to be forwarded to intended consignee's facility for further inspection.    On Wednesday, January 9, 2008, TILX 280687 was inspected by representatives of Sunoco, FRA, UTC and Conrail.  Manway cover (with Eastman seal applied; and number recorded and removed during inspection) opened and examined the manway cover gasket.  Noted the gasket on the AL side of the cover (approximately 3 o'clock position) as split completely through from the outter to inner diameter.  Split was located approximately 1" to the B-end of the manway cover bolt at that location.  Also noted 2 areas on either side of the split that had small compressions.    Photos taken by Sunoco and UTC personnel.

column168: Cargo from the BA209/04Jan arrived at the BA Cargo facility and was checked in as per normal.     On SAT the 5th of Jan 2008 US Customs came to our facility for a routine inspection, and while inspecting cargo they came upon AWB 125-33339946, 2 pieces at 170 kgs , originating from Athens, Greece, located in the warehouse. Upon the opening of these boxes they found cans of paint that were clearly marked as dangerous goods. The AWB commodity was showing spare parts.   There was no indication on the AWB or on the outside carton that there were dangerous goods inside as required by the TSA/FAA.   and IATA dangerous goods regulations   The said cargo was then put safely aside and the FAA Hazmat inspectors were notified by US Customs of the situation.   The FAA inspectors then cameto the BA Cargo facility on MON the 7th of Jan , and inspected the goods and determined that the paint was an undeclared dangerous good and should have traveled under the dangerous goods guidelines.   The FAA will now take this matter up with the CNEE/Shipper and the governing regulators in Athens Greece     BA then contacted the TSA and they advised us that since there were no security breeches or incidents they need not be involved and the correct action was taken in contacting the FAA HAZMAT Team.

column168: On January 3rd at 15:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT Florence Yard discovered OPIX21007, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances (Ethylene Glycol) dripping product from the bottom outlet area.  The car was isolated was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008-01-03-00102) assisted in notifying the shipper, Equistar Chemicals.  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product dripping from the mounting flange gasket connection between the bottom outlet valve and the tank car.  The mount flange bolts/nuts were checked for tightness and no exceptions were noted.  The entire valve area was wrapped with chemical absorbant pads and a plastic bucket was wired and taped directly under the bottom outlet valve to confine the slow drip release.  An application for FRA Movement Approval was submitted and granted on January 7th    (FRA-08010004).  After re-inspecting the tank car the container was released to destination.  Approximately one gallon of product was released.  Cause Code:  544  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

The driver sits in the cab of truck while the shipper loads the cargo tank through dome at the top. The driver thought they were done loading the cargo tank because the loader knocked on cab door and gave him the paperwork and told him he had to scale and go to the office.  The driver told the loader he would put the placards on and then the loader left.  Driver put placards on the trailer and then started to slowly pull away from the loading rack.  He said the wheels hit the chock so he got out and moved it.  He never looked up to see that the loading arm was still in the dome.  He pulled forward just a little and then noticed product spraying all over the trailer.  The loader then saw what happened  and closed the valve for the loading arm.  A construction worker that was nearby was checked out at the plant dispensery.  He had minor irritation on his face, was given some ointment, and released. The plant cleaned up the spill. The product does not have an RQ.
column169: The driver did not follow proper procedure to ensure that the cargo tank was secure before moving it.  The driver has since received performance enhancement training in decision making and safety.

column168: Driver performed his pre-trip inspection, closed the internal and external valves, then looked inside the tank and saw it had water in it.  The tankwash dried the inside of the cargo tank then our driver went to the shipper to load.  Our driver failed to recheck both the internal and external valves again and they were open.      When the shipper started loading our trailer, the product flowed out through the open valves onto the concrete.  Approximately 30 - 50 gallons was spilled into their containment.  Remediation was handled by plant personnel.
column169: This will be discussed in detail in all of our first quarter safety meetings.  We will re-enforce that it is imperative that all valves are closed before leaving our terminals.  Failure to do so will result in the appropriate disciplinary points being assigned as well as being placed with a qualifed driver trainer and retrained for a week.
column198: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.

column168: When our driver arrived at the shipper to load, he handed the operator the strapping charts for his trailer as well as a sheet of paper that outlined how much product should be loaded into each compartment.  The operator failed to check the strapping charts and did not use the suggested loading outline and assumed that compartment number three was the same size as compartment number four.  Capacity of compartment #3 is 1100 gallons and #4 is 2300 gallons.     Approximately 30 gallons of product overflowed from the # 3 compartment when it filled up and spilled onto the ground.  The product was contained and was cleaned up by plant personnel.
column169: Operators need to verify the information given on the strapping charts by comparing it to the data plate on the trailer to make sure no one has made a mistake.

column168: A California PUC inspector reported finding a leaking tank car during the course of his inspections in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately went to the track area where the leaking tank car was located. The responder found NATX 302025 with a noticeable product odor and a product stain that emanated from the manway cover. The stain on the side shell was approximately two-thirds downward on the shell. A detailed inspection by the responder revealed one manway securement bolt was not applied and the remaining five manway securement bolts were less than tool tight. The responder applied the hanging bolt and properly tool tightened all six manway securement bolts. All other valves and fittings were found to be secure. All seals applied on NATX 302025 were reported to be intact. All spillage had evaporated and product odor dissipated after the manway was secured. No ground impact from any product spillage was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: GATX 80031 a residue gasoline shipment was noted by carrier personnel with the odor of mercaptan in the area of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, U. S. Environmental, responded and found the car releasing propane from the vapor valve.  A gauge was used to determine the pressure on the car was 47 psi at the time of the release.      The shipper uses LPG to pressure off the load of gasoline and left the pressure on the car after unloading.  The vapor valve was reseated and the plug tightened stopping the release.  The car was moved to the consignee's plant to have the pressure on the car reduced to prevent further release of LPG.    .

column168: An inbound local train inspection by a BNSF carman in the railyard revealed CELX 23623 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected CELX 23623. The responder reported finding a very slow product drip at the bottom outlet valve's (BOV) belly flange. All eight of the BOV flange securement bolts were less than tool tight and the responder tool tightened these BOV flange bolts, which ended the product drip.  The responder also noticed product dampness around the top valve protective housing cover. The seal numbered 264110 was intact on the housing cover. The flange bolts for the liquid and vapor valves were found to be less than tool tight along with their corresponding closure plugs. The responder secured all these loose fittings. BNSF seal numbered 002424 was applied onto the protective housing cover. Securement and this response were concluded by 1125 hrs. CST, 1/09/08. All spillage evaporated.    Per specification stencil, CELX 23623's tank qualification was completed in 2004 by TTC TX and due in 2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While in the facility yard free product was discovered leaking from a land/sea container.  Upon further investigation it was discovered that approximately 15-gallons of free product were released outside of the container and a small amount impacted a nearby storm drain.  DOW Chemical Company responded to assess the site.  Hulcher Services, Inc. of Houston, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Hulcher Services, Inc, investigated the land/sea container and discovered that the intermodal container inside was leaking.  Hulcher Services, Inc. applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid inside of the container and on the impacted asphalt surface.  Absorbent pads were used to recover the free product from the impacted storm drain.  Hulcher Services, Inc. used a chemical transfer pump to transfer the remaining product from the leaking intermodal container into a tanker.  Seven (7) 55-gallon drum of contaminated absorbent material were generated as a result of the cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: At approximately 9:00 pm On January 2nd, 2008 , a tractor trailer dump truck was traveling North on Route 380 near exit 20 in Pennsylvania.  A vehicle, also traveling in the same direction abruptly changed lanes in front of the tractor trailer to take exit 20.  The tractor trailer attempted to stop quickly and slid on black ice.  The trailer proceeded to slide on the embankment causing the trailer to tip.  The weather temperature was 3 degrees at the time of the incident.    As a result of the "Tip" a portion of the contents of the trailer was released onto the soil.  The majority of the product remained frozen inside the trailer.  Following the incident, appropriate notifications were made to emergency response personnel including a call to 911 and the contact of our hazardous materials cleanup contractor, Rapid Response, Inc.    Rapid Response, Inc. initiated and directed the cleanup and remediation efforts related to the hazardous materials.  The hazardous material that was released was a solid that was discharged on a soil embankment. A large portion of the material release could be recovered.  However, the cleanup included the removal of contaminated soils.  All materials were properly packaged at the site and transported from the scene for shipment to the original consignee.    The following responded to the scene… PA State Police Dunmore, Covington Fire Department, Rapid Response, Inc., a hazmat cleanup contractor, and Horwith Management personnel.
column169: Based on the reports taken at the scene, the incident was generally caused by the unforeseen actions of a third party, as well as adverse weather conditions.

column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD TAKE THE TIME TO MATCH THE INFORMATION FOR THE CARGO LOADED INTO THE CONTAINER WITH THE DOCUMENTATION THAT IS PREPARED AND SUBMITTED TO THE OCEAN CARRIER. THIS WOULD PROVIDE MORE TIME FOR ANY ADDITIONAL CHECKS PRIOR TO THE CARGO BEING LOADED TO THE OCEAN CARGO VESSEL.

column168: 190 gallon cargo tank of liquid oxygen, mounted on a straight truck, blew the outer shell off while out on delivery. Incident is still under investigation. Cause has not been determined yet. The police did respond but no report has been filed as of today. Fire Dept also responded although there was no fire of any kind. The tank was filled at our facility on the morning of the incident. The driver made three stops to fill customer owned dewars (app. 41 liters each). The incident happened about six hours after the tank was filled. It appears there was an internal leak of liquid oxygen that entered the vacumm space between the inner & outer tank. This pressurized the vacumm space & caused the carbon steel outer tank to become brittle where it was in contact with the liquid oxygen. Something happened that caused the outer tank (shell) to fracture (truck might have just hit a bump in the road)& the shell was blown off the inner tank & off the truck. This tank had a road relief valve & was under low pressure. The liquid oxygen vaporized & dispersed rapidly.
column169: After researching the incident, nexAir immediately put together a new training program focused on general awareness, safety, & new procedures. All drivers, material handlers, & filling personnel participated in the training & were required to pass a written test.

The two boxes were punctured which contributed to the unintentional release which was cleaned up with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the two damaged boxes.

The driver pretripped the loaded cargo tank in the dark.  He did not notice that the chicago fitting cap for the bleeder valve on top of the trailer was not in place.  He did note that the bleeder valve was closed.  He took his hammer and went around and tightened the swing bolts on the dome lid.  Apparently the thumb hold of the Chicago fitting cap was lodged under the dome lid when it was buttoned down and allowed some product to leak out into the crashbox in transit. It was discovered when the load got to the consignee.  The driver states there was a small amount of product in the crashbox when he got to the consignee. Going by weight (which may not be entirely accurate), the consignee figures 540 pounds. That appears to be a very high estimate based on the amount in the crash box and no other signs.
column169: The driver has since received performance enhancement training on proper pre and post trip inspections.

I then wiped away the residual leakage, and patched the hole with epoxy. After the epoxy cured, th  e freight was transported on to destination. A CS-3 damage report and photos were completed.

column168: On January 24, 2008, personnel in the CSX Transportation Moncrief Yard in Jacksonville, FL observed ACFX 79862, a loaded tank car of crude sulfate turpentine, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated, the shipper was notified, and a CSX response contractor, SWWS, was dispatched to the scene with a CSX Hazmat team representative. Responders found liquid product leaking from the base flange of the liquid valve. Car would found in shell full condition with 2/4 securement nuts on the liquid valve less than wrench tight. After tightening the nuts, product continued to leak due to the overloaded state of the car. Contractor personnel removed approximately 400 gallons of product from the car and the leak stopped. Further inspection of the car revealed the following deficiencies: (1) 2 OF 4 Liquid line base flange nuts less than wrench tight, (2) 1/8 manway cover bolts less than wrench tight,  (3) The tank was overdue for test  last tested in 1997 and due in 2007, (4) 2/4 Placards faded, and (5) manway cover gasket deteriorated. CSX took possession of the car from Norfolk Southern on 1/24/2008 for a switch move to the consignee. A special switch move was required for this car.    NARRI Severity Index Values   Scoring Calulation: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0)  = 60

At the time of the incident, Mr. Jim O'Connor was driving the propane delivery truck for Clarinda Cooperative.  Weather conditions were snow and blowing snow with wind speeds 30 - 35 mph. from the north.  As Mr. O'Connor traveled west on 290th. St., he crested a hill and discovered the gravel road surface to be completely covered with ice.  Mr. O'Connor lost control of the vehicle and it entered the road ditch and overturned.  The accident damaged the vapor return piping on the rear head of the cargo tank motor vehicle.      The damaged piping allowed the liquid propane inside the cargo tank to release to the atmosphere.  The propane liquid immediately volitalized to a vapor.  The vapor cloud dispersed rapidly with the strong north winds.  There was no fire or explosion as a result of this release.    Mr. O'Connor notified his supervisor of the accident.  The Taylor County Sheriff's office and the Blockton Volunteer Fire Department responded to the release.  The Taylor County Sheriff's Office called for the closure of 290th. St. for a length of one mile, commencing with Yellowstone Ave. at the east end.  A single residence was evacuated at 3261 290 th. St. as a precautionary measure.  No other residences or businesses were located in the vicinity of the release.  The strong north wind dispersed the propane vapor cloud over open agricultural fields.    Officials of Clarinda Cooperative and the Blockton Volunteer Fire Department surveyed the scene and determined that an attempt could be made to close the valve leading to the damaged piping.  The attempt to close the valve occurred at approximately 1:30 p.m.  The attempt to close the valve was not completely successful and officials determined that they would let the balance of the propane in the cargo tank vent to the atmosphere.    The propane release ended at approximately 5:30 p.m.  A wrecker was called in to set the propane delivery vehicle back on it's wheels and return the truck to the roadway.    Once the truck was towed from the scene, the Taylor County Sheriff's Office opened 290th. St to traffic and allowed the evacuees to return to their residence.
column169: All drivers will evaluate weather and road conditions when deliveries have to be made during inclement weather.

column168: PROX 43707 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported sloshing product from the manway cover area during movement in the railyard. PROX 43707 was isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected PROX 43707 finding no active leaking, but product staining on both sides of the tank side shell. The stains emanated from the manway nozzle/cover. Inspection of the manway securement bolts revealed all six bolts were less than tool tight (finger loose). Responders properly tool tightened the manway securement bolts. After this securement was completed, PROX 43707 was moved and no further product release was evident during this movement in the railyard. The spillage on the side shell evaporated and no product ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 1730 hrs. CST, 01/28/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver was making his transfer hose connection from the tanker compartment to the truck mounted pump inlet when he failed to secure the camlock ears at the pump connection. The customer had come and "distracted him" with a question while making the connection and he did not double check to insure that both ears were clamped down. Driver then opened the internal valve and the external valve prior to engaging the pump. Driver noticed the product leaking and immediately closed both the internal and external valves (pump was never engaged). Estimated amount that spilled was approx 5-7gal in jump hose. Customer immediately responded by containing spilled product with "kitty litter" and assisted driver in complete clean up. Customer to properly dispose of clean up material per state and federal regulations.
column169: Driver was inherited in recent competitor buyout and was new to his former company with limited training. Corrective actions for this incident are the following: 1. Use of velcro straps at each hose connection to insure camlock ears are completely closed (completed). 2. Perform refresher training on Univar USA standard operating procedures relating to tanker load/unload processes (in process). 3. Perform a thorough site inspection using the Univar Customer Bulk Profile form (completed). 4. Review tanker/pump connections to insure better control of product flow (fixed pipe on fender to be removed).

column168: Univar driver was making a delivery of 4 drums of Phosphoric Acid 75% to customer (Electrolux / Husqvarna Outdoor Products) in Orangeburg, SC. As the customers fork lift driver was attempting to unload the pallet of four drums from our trailer he went in too high with his forks and punctured one of the drums. He removed the pallet from our trailer and placed the leaking drum in a contained area. The leaking drum left a trail of material about  5 inches wide and about 30 feet long in our trailer the remaining material was spilled on a concrete floor and containment area at the customers facility. I spoke with the customers Environmental and Health Manager and he said that they assumed all responsibility and would get the material cleaned up by neutralizing the material and using absorbent to remove the liquid. I was in phone contact with the driver during the clean up and he said the customer new exactly what to do and they did a real good and safe job of cleaning up the spill. Within an hour our trailer was cleaned and driver was released to continue his deiveries. No other material on the trailer was damaged or contaminated by the spilled material. In all it was estimated that about 15 gals of material was spilled from the damaged drum but it was all contained and cleaned up by the customer.
column169: Customer to perform additional fork truck training.

column168: At 1400 on 1/30 Anthony Brown of Atlantic Southeast Airlines tendered to Delta Cargo, awb 006 6830 9975 for shipment to Atlanta.  Air waybill stated the shipment contained COMAT, “Aircraft Parts” and the package was labeled as “AOG (Aircraft on Ground) – Rush Shipment”. The shipment was presented to TSA for security screening.  During ETD screening, TSA received a positive alarm.  Delta Cargo was contacted to send an agent to witness/assist with opening the package in attempt to clear the alarm.  The package was opened, TSA cleared the alarm and ok-ed shipment for movement, however, Delta Agent Jim Lytle realized the shipment was not as described on the waybill and informed DL Supervisor, Joe Dacek.  The shipment was actually a remote control, methanol-mixture fueled boat which contained what appeared to be residual fuel.  Cincinnati Cargo operation contacted Delta’s Corporate Dangerous Goods Management Group to report the incident and ask for further guidance.
column169: Delta's Corporate Dangerous Goods Management Group contacted ASA's Compliance Department and briefed them on the incident.  ASA Corporate Compliance and maintenance are engaged and investigating.

column168: SCMX 4359 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported venting in the railyard. SCMX 4359 was cordoned off awaiting detailed inspection. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected SCMX 4359 and reported a product vapor hiss emanating from the thermometer well cap. The well cap was finger loose and the responder tool tightened the cap which eliminated any further venting. No liquid product was found. A contract responder conducted air monitoring around SCMX 4359 and found no detectable product emissions. In addition, the inspection revealed that the vapor line's closure plug was loose. Responders removed the screw type closure plug, applied Teflon tape to the threads and properly secured the plug. No product vapor was detected at this loose closure plug. Securement was completed by 1614 hrs. CST, 1/30/08. Disposition for home shop was requested for SCMX 4359 for further inspection and necessary repairs to the thermometer well piping which most likely incurred a breach.      SCMX 4359's side specification stencil indicated that the latest tank qualification date was 2002 and is due in 2012.

column168: While making a switching move in the our Port facility, the conductor noticed tank car number RSLX3O23 leaking from the top of the car. Mississippi Department of Environmental Control and Mississippi Department of Transportation was contacted. They contacted FRA and the Hancock County EOC as well as the car owner. column168: Shipment was loaded at origin facility in between skids of other freight.  The haz mat shipment was loaded on the floor, and no dunnage was used to surround it and protect it from other freight in the trailer.  The other freight was not blocked and braced properly, and during transit to the unloading facility, skids shifted and crushed the drum.  Plastice sidewalls of drum were punctured by the corner of one of the skids, releasing contents.  When trailer arrived at unloading facility and leak was discovered, supervisor contacted Haz Mat One Emergency Response Services.  Haz Mat One dispatched environmental contractor to scene to clean spill and dispose of waste.
column169: Notice sent to loading facility to review loading practices.  Emphasis on use of dunnage around drums and haz mat, as well as proper blocking and bracing. column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was temporarily staged at a transportation related facility operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. pending continued transportation to the intended disposal facility.  While in temporary storage, it was discovered that residual liquid, not evident at the time the container was loaded, had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the bottom of the container.  Approximately one pound of material escaped from the container onto the floor of the van trailer where it was prevented from escaping to the environment.  Upon discovery of the release, facility personnel developed a response plan and proceeded to take all necessary corrective action to place the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum and remediate and containerize all material that had escaped from the package.  The recovered material along with all clean-up debris was placed into the salvage drum and was sent for disposal to the waste management facility identified on the hazardous waste manifest
column169: At the time of loading, all containers were inspected and no evidence of damage and or structural integrity were noted or identified.  Both the shipper offering the containers for transportation and the driver accepting the containers for transportation were instructed to continue to inspect all containers prior to transportation and to take necessary corrective actions such as placing in salvage drum should a container of questionable integrity be identified.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route between the shipper’s location and the intended waste management facility.   During the course of transportation, the driver made a routine stop at an in transit storage location operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc.  During the course of transportation, an inspection of the shipment identified approximately 1 gallon of material had escaped from a crack in the bottom of a 55 gallon container.  Facility personnel developed a response plan and entered the trailer for the purpose of placing the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum as well as containerizing the released material.  Upon inspection of the container, it was discovered at the drum was impacted by a sharp object not identified at the time the container was loaded.  The response team placed the container into a salvage drum along with all clean-up debris that included the released material and the material used to decontaminate the floor of the van trailer.  This container was then sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time of loading, the driver inspected the containers and found no evidence of damage and/or leaks.  It is believed that during the course of transportation, the drum came in contact with a sharp object that caused a minor crack.  The driver has been instructed that prior to loading any vehicle, the floor of the trailer must be inspected for any foreign objects that could damage a container.  In addition, each pallet is to be inspected to insure that there are no protruding fastening devices and/or broken slats that could damage a container during transportation.

column168: After take off from Miami International Airport, climbing above 10,000 feet, at approximately 1:00 PM EST, the load supervisor entered the cargo compartment to check the security of the cargo. The load supervisor noticed a strongsmell, left cargo compartment and notified the Captain. Returned to cargo compartment with gloves and oxygen mask, discovered one box oozing an unknown fluid. Took Pictures then opened box and found two of four 4 liter cans of paint bent/crushed and leaking. Approximately 200 ML of fluid total escaped from the two cans. The two leaking cans were sealed in a plastic bag which then stopped the paint fumes from contaminating the air in the aircraft. The fumes never reached the flight deck. The paint did not contaminate the aircraft structure, as it remained on the shipping pallet, the flight continued to destination (Quito, Ecuador) without further incident, at which point the damaged cargo was unloaded by the company that chartered our aircraft.(SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS)

Our employee arrived at the customer and was showed where to hook up and unload; customer signed off on Freight Bill and Bill of Lading.  After about an hour and a half of unloading, driver was abruptly told to stop unloading due to storage overflow.  Our employee was hooked up to a manifold that was in-turn hooked up to three storage tanks.  It operated in such a fashion, that when one storage tank was full, it would move to one of the other two until all three were filled.  The valve that controls this was not set properly causing the one storage tank to overflow.  Customer fixed the problem and our driver continued to unload.  Customer took full responsibility.
column169: This incident was completely human error on behalf of the customer.  Our employee followed all procedures to prevent such an occurrence.  No corrective action was taken on behalf of our employee.

LEAKING..CONTAINED IN RECOVERY DRUM

Driver was making delivery of the material. Given written confirmation by consignee's agent that their storage tank capacity would hold the 4819 gallons shipped.  The material was to be off loaded by carrier's pump and chemical hoses.  Material would be pumped to customer's storage tank.  Split between two storage tanks.  Storage tanks are inside the building out of our drivers line of sight. Consignee assigned two of their operators to assist our driver with the unloading process. One inside to monitor their tank levels and the other outside with our driver.  Both operators were in radio communication with each other.  The first tank was filled then they switched to the second tank.  As it was getting close to maximum capacity, the storage tank vented spilling 10-15 gallons into their containment.
column169: From a carriers position, the driver did as he was instructed.  This is a consignee/operator issue.

column168: Univar driver, Daniel Espinoza, was delivering Hydrogen Peroxide 50% to Dow Chemical in Pittsburg, CA on sales order SJ840497. After connecting the hose to customer’s storage tank T-1020 loading connection, Daniel proceeded to start the off-loading process. Immediately after product transfer began, Dow operator Jeffrey Sutton, noticed a small leak then a pretty good stream coming from the connection; Univar driver stated all connections were secure via orange velcro straps. Dow operator immediately notified Univar driver of the problem and the tank truck pump and product discharge valve were shut off. Approximately 1 gallon of Hydrogen Peroxide 50% was discharged from the fitting into a diked containment area. Succeeding the shut off, the fitting was secured via shims and the leak was stopped.
column169: Connections should be double checked before unloading process begins. Hoses and gaskets are to be inspected before every use. Product valves should be opened slowly to enable operator to monitor connections for leaks.

Employee filled a tank too full due to a faulty gage on the tank.  The Employee had to administer a controlled release of 75 gallons slowly for about two hours to get the gage down to 80%.  During the controlled release a screw on the relief valve came out.  The employee tried to replace the screw and this is when the employee was burnt on his thumb.  The employee later found a small hole in this thumb area of his gloves.
column169: The gage on the tank will be replaced before the next delivery is made.  There have been no deliveries to this tank since this incident occurred.

column168: THE EMPLOYEE GEAN SEARS WAS DRIVING AMERIGAS BOBTAIL NUMBER 13 FALCON ROAD IN FEFFERSON COUNT, TN.  HE WAS TRAVELING WEST APPROACHING A CURVE TRAVELING AT 35 MPH.  BEFORE GETTING TO THE CURVE HE LET OFF OF THE ACCELORATOR.  HE WAS THEN TRAVELING AT 25 MMPH.  HE THEN ATTEMPTED THE CURVE.  THE LEFT REAR WHEEL WENT OFFF OF THE PAVEMENT AND THE DRIVER HIT THE BRAKES.  HE THEN ATTMPTED TO TURN THE STEERING WHEELBACK TO THE LEFT WHICH WOULD HAVE DIRECTED THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  HE FAILED AT THIS.  UPON DOING SO THE  BACK OF THE VEHICLE CAME OFF OF THE GROUND AND THEN THE VEHICLE TIPPED OVER ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE.  THE VEHICLE THEN SLID ABOUT TWENTY FIVE FEET ON THE GOURND, TAKING DOWN A FENCE ON PROPERTY THAT BELONGS TO.  AT THIS POINT THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST.  THE DRIVER CLIMBED OUT OF THE PASSENGER SIDE WINDOW.  NO PROPANE WAS RELEASED.
column169: I FEEL THAT SPEED WAS A FACTOR.  THE REDUCTION OF SPEED POSSIBLE COULD HAVE RESULTED IN AVOIDING THIS ACCIDENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED WITH A DELIVERY OF HOME HEATING OIL INTO A 550 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. THE TANK WAS LOCATED AROUND THE FAR SIDE OF THE RESIDENCE. DURING THE DELIVERY A DROP IN PRESSURE WAS NOTICE. THE DRIVER CLOSED THE DELIVERY NOZZLE AND STARTED BACK TOWARD THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRUCK. ALL VALVES WERE IMMEDIACY CLOSED AND THE PUMP STOPPED. THE DRIVER THEN WORKED TO IMMEDIATELY CONTAIN THE PRODUCT WITH ALL MEANS POSSIBLE. EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS ALSO CALLED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED. INSPECTION OF THE TRUCK SHOWED THAT THE COMPRESSION COUPLING ON THE END OF THE DELIVERY HOSE FAILED (CAME APART). IT WAS THE END OF THE HOSE ATTACHED TO THE HOSE REALER. WITH THE USE OF ABSORPTION PADS AND BOOMS, MOST OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND COLLECTED IN A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME. THE GROUND WAS ALSO FROZEN AT THE TIME, WHICH AIDED IN THE COLLECTION. DATOM PRODUCTS (DUNMORE, PA) WAS HIRED TO CLEAN THE SITE AND HAD AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW AT THE SITE SHORTLY AFTER THEY WERE CALLED. PA DEP ALSO SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SITE. ROBERT M. BISIGNANI OF PA DEP ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND WAS PLEASED WITH THE INITIAL RESPONSE. DATOM WILL CONTINUE TO MONITOR WATER SAMPLES AND WORK WITH DEP TO ENSURE THE SITE REMAINS CLEAN.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1:48 P.M. SUNBELT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (SUNBELT) WAS RETAINED BY STEVE COOK OF SOLAR TRANSPORT TO RESPOND TO A GASOLINE SPILL AT RANDY’S PLACE CONVENIENCE STORE IN. KNOB NOSTER, MO.  A SOLAR TRANSPORT FUEL TANKER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO AN ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 40 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED OUTSIDE OF A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT. THE FUEL HAD SOAKED INTO SOIL AT THE EDGE OF A CONCRETE PARKING AREA.  SUNBELT USED A BACKHOE TO REMOVE APPROXIMATELY 17 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND THEN BACKFILLED THE AREA BARROW MATERIAL.  SAMPLES OF THE AREA WERE TAKEN AFTER EXCAVATION. IT APPEARS PREVIOUS OVERFILLS IN THIS AREA HAVE OCCURRED. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE CONCRETE IN THIS AREA HAS CRACKS AND IS AGED.  NO FURTHER ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN AT THIS SITE.  A FULL SITE REPORT WILL FOLLOW ONCE COMPLETED.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon offloading at customer location, a leak was discovered.  Apparently, there was a defect in the closure on one (1) 95-gallon tote.  Approximately one (1) gallon of free product was released.  Shipper was consulted, and a Material Safety Data Sheet was referenced.  Clean Harbors Environmental of Sacramento, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Clean Harbors Environmental scraped the dried product from the affected area, and oversaw the product transfer into one (1) 250-gallon tote.  The damaged tote was washed out, and waste water was placed, along with the free product, into the one (1) 250-gallon tote.  One (1) 250-gallon tote of free product and wash water was left on site, pending disposition from the shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release appears to be related to a defective closure on the tote, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safety guidelines to all personnel.

column168: On 1/24/2008 at 0100, the switching crew detected an odor coming from tank car SCMX 5016, a residue car last containing HEXENE UN2370.They contacted the yardmaster,who contacted the New Orleans Fire Dept. Hazardous Materials Unit, Harbor Police,Louisiana State Police Hazardous Materials Office, and myself. I immediately contacted United States Environmental Services. The shipper, Shell Chemical was also notified. U.S.E.S arrived and determined the gasket around the thermometer well was leaking. They put a gasket on the thermo well and the car was isolated on track 5. the shippers' representatives arrived and the car was pressurized with nitrogen to check for leaks a second leak was found around the liquid line. U.S.E.S. told the shipper they had to ger rescar to repair the second leak and re-certify the car. This was done and the car was released. L.S.P. Item # 0800447 was closed at 1242.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver team stopped at our operating center enroute to the consignee with loaded compartment cargo tank.  While parked there, they noticed some product leaking out of the pressure relief vent on top of compartment #3.  It was determined that by running heat in transit required to warm the product, the product expanded and came out the vent.  The heat in transit was turned off and the leak stopped.  We had our emergency response vendor come out to clean up the spill. The cargo tank had no more issues in transit or during delivery.
column169: We've never had an issue like that before.  It's possible that more product was loaded in that compartment than requested (requested was 200 gallons below legal limit) and the heat and sloshing forced it out the vent.  The other compartments were also heated and no issues reported with any leaks.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a customer location. The driver failed to follow procedure at took two hoses out at once. The driver connected one hose to the diesel tank in the ground. The driver picked up the wrong hose to connect to the tanker. The driver failed to trace his hose back. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product once he realized what had occured but approximately 15 gallons spilled into the concrete containment area. All fuel was contained on spill pads and no fuel reached soil or drains.
column169: The driver failed to follow to steps in the proper unloading procedures. Driver was re-trained on unloading procedures. Incident prevention observations were performed and the driver was paired with a Driver Trainer for an additional period of time.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering diesel to a client location. The driver began to unload into a manifolded tank. The driver was delivering just over 1000 gallons. The driver took the veeder root reading and the stick reading of one tank, it showed he had just over 500 gallons of room. The driver failed to stick the second tank and assumed it also had 500 gallons of room. The two tanks had not equilized and upon unloading fuel began to leak out of the fill hole. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product but approximately 10 gallons leaked into the concrete area. No fuel reached soil or drains. The driver and the fire department cleaned up the spill to the satisfaction of AR Brooks. The fire department supplied absorbent powder, pads, foam and water.
column169: The driver was re-trained on the unloading procedures and observed by a safety supervisor while unloading.

column62: Human Error; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: The shipment in question arrived Butte Mt. in a combination semi-tractor and two 28 foot trailers. The trailers were put to the dock for unloading. Two ConWay employees were unloading the trailer with a fork lift. When they reached the shipment in question they noticed that they had leaked material under the pallet and at that time notified me, Lawrence McGillvray, the supervisor on shift. I had them stay away from the spill untill I could retrieve the proper paper work for the freight and call the emergency hotline and determine the extent of the emergency. It was determined that we needed to clean the spill with floor dry and dispose of it in a O.P drum along with the leaking pails. It was determined that the pails had been stacked too high on the pallet and the weight of the upper pails crushed the bottom layerof pails in transit. When the bottom pails crushed they also cracked which led to the pails leaking. The material in the pails was the consistency of heavy syrup so there lease was only about 1 gallon.
column169: Shipper should take into consideration the weight of filled pails to determine the the number of pails that can safely be stacked for transit.

column168: UPRR s Response Management Communications Center notified Lane A. Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials of a derailment involving UTLX 200553. Mr. Sekavec proceeded to the derailment and found the car laying en its right side to the south of the track. Upon inspection, Mr. Sekavec found no active release and no bottom outlet on the car. The release appeared to have come from the top of the car and then ran down the south side of the car. There was a stain on the ballast approximately 20 feet long on the south side of the car that appeared to have splashed out of the top of the car.  Mr. Sekavec requested the Kansas City, KS, Fire Department respond to rinse the car off to neutralize any product still remaining on the tank. Information from the shipper (Evonic Degussa) indicated that dilution with water was a proper neutralization and hazard elimination technique. Following dilution, Mr.  Sekavec climbed to the top of the car to check the pressure relief device rupture disk and verified that it was still intact. Due to the position of the car, he was unable to access any of the other valves to verify their security. During rerailing operations, the tank car turned further onto its right side and approximately 400-500 gallons of product were released from an unknown location underneath the combination housing cover. KCKFD was requested to respond again and apply water to neutralize and dilute the released material. Following the application, the car was stabilized and brought back to an upright orientation. Mr. Sekavec then checked the remaining valves and fittings, finding them all apparently secure with no signs of where the product was released. The car was then set back on  truck on the rail for transloading.The material that had pooled on the ballast was diluted until no more reaction was taking place with the organic material in the ground. Mr. Sekavec met with representatives from the EPA and Kansas Department of Health and Environment who responded to the incident. Mr. Sekavec conferred with them and advised the shipper s advice was to dilute the material with copious amounts of water and then remove the affected material from the area. Both KDHE and EPA advised that would an acceptable means of remediation.The excavated material was spread out on a flat area adjacent to the derailment site and soaked with water again after being leveled. That material will be allowed to stay in place following its remediation since there is no remaining hazard.The cause of the release remains under investigation. UTLX and the shipper were both notified as to the particulars of the incident to assist in determining the source of the release.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DERAILMENT.

column168: I was called in to respond to a chemical release on trailer CTRQ-22109. When I arrived on location at Con-Way Freight in Kettleman City, CA when I saw a trailer that had some substance hanging from the dot inspection bar. I investigated this leak and saw that this shipment was not secured properly and fell over. The freight shifted in a manner that it was pinned between a bigger crate behind it and the remainder of the freight that was in front. This shift in transit caused a five gallon pail of adhesive to be released enroute from Abeline, TX to Kettleman City, CA. The metal pail was lying on its side and punctured, releasing the adhesive product. There was not much that you could do but clean up what dried up and recoupe the remainder of the shipment and move to destination.
column169: I would recommend that the Abilen, TX facility due some extra training with this individual and retrain him on proper loading and securing shipments in a manner that they would not shift as much in transit.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKINGS, REMOVING AND RANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMCIALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: On 01/11/2008, a non-specification fiberboard box (package) containing two (2) vial of an expired radiopharmaceutical product (lndium-111 Chloride) was offered to Federal Express for air transportation. The package was shipped from one company location (Houston, TX) to another company location (Hazelwood, MO). The total activity for this consignment was approximately 2.1 E-7 Curie at the time of offering.On 01/14/2008, personnel at the Hazelwood, MO location discovered that the package containing the lndium-111radiopharmaceutical product was not offered for transportation pursuant to 49 CFR 173.421. The radioactive material (radiopharmaceutical) was appropriately collected and placed into storage by the site Radiation Safety Officer. There was no release of radioactive material and no report of unnecessary radiation exposure and/or contamination to employees.

column168: Kevin Heyen, Train Dispatcher 26.5 WS04039, reported a derailment on northbound Train MHOKC 31, Lead Locomotive UP 4337, at Mile Post 220.00 of the Los Springs Subdivision, north of Whitewater, KS. At 07:49 PM, Paul Eck, Director of Network Control, stated eleven railcars were derailed, lines thirty through forty in the consist, in unknown positions. Paul stated there was no release of product and no vapor cloud, although hazardous materials were contained in some of the railcars involved. Federal notification was issued based on speculated damage costs. Michael Moore, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. He also contracted HazMat Response, Contractor, to respond to the derailment site. Hazmat Response arrived on scene and advised that tank car STEX 1 3577,GATX 2121 0,UTLX 96170, and DOWX 8213 were all secure and not leaking. Tank car NATX 37720 was leaking a small drip, from the liquid valve flange. A poly-pool was placed underneath Tankcar NATX 37720 and would remain in place pending further uprighting efforts. When tankcar NATX 37720 was uprighted the leak was stopped. Tankcars STEX 1 3577,GATX 21210, NATX 37720 were staged to be transtered at a later date.

column168: David Barry, Manager of Yard Operations, reported Tankcar NATX 33158 was releasing product from the top of the car in the Beaumont, TX Railyard. Timothy O'Brien, Program Director of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. Upon arrival, Mr. O'Brien inspected the tank car and found the B-end liquid valve leaking from the flange at the pressure plate. All four nuts securing the valve to the pressure plate were tightened, stopping the leak. All other valves were inspected and found to be in good order. The car was released.
column169: REVIEW CONTRACT LOADER (MARTIN GAS) PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS.

column168: INITIAL REPORT  Kerry Douglas, Manager of Yard Operations, reported employees noticed a taint odor near the south end of Bawl Track 9, Livonia Rail yard, Livonia, LA. Mr. Douglas stated the source of the odor could not be determined, there were no reports of injuries or exposures, and requested a Manager Hazardous Materials respond to investigate. Thomas Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. After inspecting several tank cars in the bowl yard, tank car RAIX 6640 was found to be the source of the odor. It was estimated that the car had released less than one ounce of ethyl acrylate. The leakage was from the base of the 2 inch liquid valve were it threads onto the education pipe nipple. The valve body could be turned by hand and a pipe wrench was used by Robinson to secure the valve. Temeka, Pointe Coupee Parish Sheriff Dispatcher, was notified. State regulatory agencies were also notified.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  THE LEAKAGE FROM THE TANK CAR WAS FROM THE BASE OF THE 2 INCH LIQUID VALVE WHERE IT THREADS ONTO THE EDUCTION PIPE NIPPLE.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD REVIEW TNK CAR SECUREMENT PROCESS.

column168: Carlos Strait, North Platte Corridor Manager, reported Tankcar UTLX 203500 had released an unknown amount of product after humping the tankcar in Yard One, Track 37 of the Bailey Yard in North Platte, NE. The North Platte Corridor Manager advised the liquid was evaporating and there were no injuries, no waterways effected or reports of inhalation. Lane Sekavec, Manager of Hazardous Material Field Operations, was notified. State regulatory agency notifications were completed.  All 1:00 AM, Sekavec  advised the release was from the top of the tankcar after humping and there was no release onto the ground. Mr. Sekavec advised all the product had evaporated. Mr. Sekavec advised he was awaiting contact from the shipper and Haz-Mat Response, Contractor, would be contracted to inspect the tankcar. At 11:28AM, Sekavec advised he had not been contacted by the shipper and he was prceeding with contractor inspection of the tankcar. At 02:45 PM, Sekavec stated the tankcar had been inspected by Haz-Mat Response personnel and they determined the release was due to a defective pressure relief valve. The railcar was bad ordered and set aside for completion of repairs on Monday, but since there was no active release, the incident was closed.
column169: ENSURE PROPER MAINTENANCE AND INSPECTION OF TANK CAR EQUIPMENT.

column58: Frangible Disc; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: John Valley, Manager of Terminal Operations, reported tank car GATX 60916 was venting from the top at Track 307 in the Livonia Rail yard in Livonia, LA. Mr. Valley confirmed the tank car was isolated and advised no personnel exposures had occurred. Tom Robinson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was contacted and confirmed he was already aware of the incident and was responding. State regulatory agencies were notified.  Inspection by Robinson revealed that the frangible disc in the safety vent assembly had ruptured. A new 165-pound disc of similar design replaced the ruptured 165-pound disc. Any product that had been released had either evaporated or dried and no further remediation was indicated.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: Wes Keyland, Yard Master, reported product released from Tankcar UTLX 208112 on the west end of Track 25 in the West Colton Railyard in Rialto, CA. Robert Bavier, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. At 09:00 AM, Bavier advised this was a vapor release only caused by a loose manway cover and no product touched the ground. At 10:17 AM, Bavier he had tightened the manway cover and remediation was complete.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: John Miller, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, and Richard Wuiff, Alton & Southern, reported Tankcar GATX 71081 released product from the bottom outlet valve in the East St. Louis Yard, which Is Mile Post 283.5 of the Church Industrial Lead in East St. Louis, IL. Mr. Miller advised the lever handle was disengaged and the outlet valve cap was not attached. Miller closed the valve, however the cap was unable to be secured on the tankcar. Mr. Miller requested Chemtrec be notified for shipper contact. Mr. Miller advised the tankcar was secure, however, would not be released until repaired by the shipper. State notifications were completed. At 02:24 PM, Miller advised Hulcher Services, Contractor, would be replacing the cap on the bottom outlet valve on 01/07/2008 and the tankcar would then be released for shipment.

UPRR Carman, reported product was dripping from top of tankcar GATX 80568 in the Alfalfa Railyard, El Paso, TX. John Jackson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. Mr. Jackson discovered product contained on top of the car due to loose liquid line valve. Mr. Jackson notified Viva Environmental to respond to clean the product from the car. Mr. Jackson also determined the packing nut on the liquid line valve handle was leaking due to defective packing around the valve handle shaft. Mr. Jackson and Viva personnel tightned the loose valve and repacked the valve shaft stopping the release. The car was reinspected and released to destination with no other exceptions. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec
column169: SHIPPER WILL REVIEW LOADING/UNLOADING AND T/C SECUREMENT PROCESS AND TRAINING.

column168: The Conductor of Train 211 failed to see a second derail when backing PROX 14125 sulfuric acid into Track 1 at theKidders GAG Chemical Plant. The load of sulfuric acid struck the derail and derailed the south truck (B End) to the east with the south end of the car starting slightly down into the roadside ditch. The north end of the car remained coupled to4 loads and a locomotive which prevented the car from rolling further into the ditch. The car came to rest leaning about 40 degrees. No tank damage, no failure of the packaging and no leaks.On Saturday, January 19, 2008 MMA attempted to right the car with a 150 ton railway crane. Due to the angle and distance from the derailed tank the crane was unable to make the lift. GAC Chemical was requested by MMA totransload the product from the derailed tank into an adjacent empty (residue) tank that was positioned along side thederailed load. During the transfer between the two tanks a small amount of product escaped through the loosed manwayon the adjacent tank car. The loss of product was estimated to be less than 140 pounds or 10 gallons. (Note: It wasnecessary to loosen the cover to accomodate pressure changes in the tank during transfer. The discharge was referredto by GAC Chemical as a burp) The local fire department was available at the derailment site during the transfer ofproduct. The fire crew was asked by GAC to wet the tank down using approximately 300 gallons of water to dilute theproduct.The tank was not damaged during the derailment and the discharge of product at the manway cover was not caused bytank or car apparatus failure.-

column168: THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED LOADING AND WAS DISCONNECTING THE LINES. WHEN BREAKINGS THE LINES THE DRIVER HEARD A “POP” AND NOTICED A LEAK ON THE “BLOW DOWN LINE”. THE DRIVER ACTIVATED ALL EMERGENCY VALVES AND CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONDERS. APPROXIMATELY 1400 GALLONS OF LPC WAS LOST. THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES AND NO FIRE. APPROXIMATELY FORTY PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FOR ABOUT THREE HOURS AND A SECTION OF RAIL ROAD WAS SHUT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED ONTO ANOTHER TRANSPORT AND THE CARGO TANK INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS TAKEN TO THE HOLTON TRANSPORT FACILITY THEN ON TO ELITE TRAILER SALES AND SERVICE, INC. 1800 LINDER INDUSTRIAL DRIVE NASHVILLE, TN 37209 FOR INSPECTION REPAIR AND COMPLETE RECERTIFICATION. DEBRIS WAS FOUND UNDER THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE IN THE TANK WHICH PREVENTED IT FROM CLOSING.
column169: THE CARGO TANK INVOLVED WAS TAKEN TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION, REPAIR AND COMPLETE RECERTIFICATION. A NEW EXCESS FLOW VALVE WAS INSTALLED AND HYDROSTATIC, PRESSURE AND MAGNETIC PARTICLE TESTING IS BEING PERFORMED BEFORE THE UNIT IS PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN EXTENSIVELY INTERVIEWED AND COUNSELED ON THIS INCIDENT. THE DRIVER HAS OVER FIVE YEARS LPG EXPERIENCE BUT WILL BE RE—TRAINED AND RE—CERTIFIED BEFORE BEING ALLOWED TO RETURN TO LPG DUTY. HOLTON TRANSPORT IS CONDUCTING RE—TRAINING AND ADDITIONAL SAFETY TRAINING WITH ALL EMPLOYEES WITH EMPHASIS ON PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES, INSPECTION OF ALL VALVES AND CONTROLS AND PROPER EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN PROCEDURES.

column168: Truck was loaded in San Jose Ca and the destination was San Bruno Ca. The unit was traveling on 101 N/B at Woodside St when a out of control van hit the rear axle causing the unit to flip to the left. The trailer turned over on the freeway and by the time the driver got the unit stopped the leak had started. As the trailer was on it's side and being dragged it finally opened up a small area on the left side of trailer causing a 2600 gallons spill on the freeway. All agency's responded Fire Department, NRC Environement, Redwood City Police Department, Coast Guard, Dept Fish & Game and San Mateo County Officals. Also members of Kag West Management Safety team showed up. All agency's were notified as well including OES. Part of the freeway was repaved due to the fuel spill.

column168: Gory Hood, Manager of Operating Practices, reported a train conductor employee was exposed on the face to a small amount of blown Sulfuric Acid released from the top seal of Tankcar KCCX 3335 in the Mojave Yard in Mojave, CA. The tankcar was isolated on Track One at the northend of the yard and the employee was sent to the hospital for medical treatment. Robert Bavier, Manager of Hazardous Materials, responded. The tankcar rupture disk housing was damaged to the point of no repair (the tri-vent rupture disc housing had three cracks,the disc, disc retainer and inspection cap were all missing). There was no evidence of a disk being in tne rupture disc housing. The tank was decontaminated and a full replacement of the rupture disc housing conducted.

The conductor was splashed with the product during move-ment of the car and vapor exposure to throat/chest.  3. N/A (no fatality)  4. Employee received burn on the side of the face from product.  5. Chemical burn to face was 1st degree to approximately 25%-35% of side of face.  6. Bum was on the  side of face approximately 25-35%.  7. Burn was a chemical burn from product (Sulfuric Acid).  8. Yes. Employee was taken to the hospital for medical evaluation and treatment. Employee was not hospitalized. Received treatment and given topical non-prescription  ointment (Neosporin).  9. Yes. Employee first day off was 2/2/2008 and as to date(4/1 5/08) has not returned to work.  10. Employee  was wearing following PPE -- Safety Shoes, Safety Glasses, and other gloves.  11. Seen by primary Dr. on 2/5/08, had a breathing test, was prescribed 2 inhalers, a decongestant, and an antibiotic.  Dr. also ordered toxicology screening to include blood and urine. Results not known at this time.

On January 15th , 2008, at approximately 3:00 a.m. CST, a tractor-trailer operated by KLLM Transport Services, was traveling on 1-10 west at approximately mile marker 817 when the driver noticed a rear trailer tire was on fire. The driver immediately pulled over and attempted to extinguish the fire. The fire began to intensify so the driver dropped the trailer and pulled the tractor forward. Apparently, the brake hub had locked up causing the fire. The driver then notified his dispatch of the incident and called 911. The trailer contained sixty-two (62), 55-gallon drums of methane sulfonic acid.

column168: Ashland driver attempting delivery of 1500 gal of HS 2790 Blend (UN1263) to Altivity Packaging in Milwaukee, WI. Customer required truck assisted pump off into their storage tank. Ashland driver reversed connections between tanker-pump-storage tank resulting in material being sucked out of customers storage tank and into a 2000 gal. capacity compartment on tank wagon. Reversal of pump caused material to over fill compartment at which point it began spilling out of the compartment manway at the top of the truck. Investigation revealed that at the time this was occurring the Ashland driver was inside the cab of the truck with customer associate instead of actively monitoring pump and connections. Another customer associate alerted our driver to the fact that a spill was in process at which point our driver shutoff the flow of material by disengaging the pump. Driver assessed the situation and quickly with the assistance of on-site employees moved to contain and clean up the spill. Fire and Police responders were contacted and proceeded to assist with the mitigation and clean up of the spill. Ashland also called in Veolia Environmental in an emergency reponse capacity to complete the clean up and assessment of the spill.
column169: Root cause analysis of this event has determined that this spill was entirely preventable and a result of human error/ negligence on the part of Ashland driver. Driver in question has over 15 years experience delivering bulk chemical products and should have executed the delivery without incident as well as been in position to monitor transfer process to prevent this type of event. As a result of this incident Ashland has proceeded to intensify its bulk transfer process training and refresher training. We have also invested in visual aids and equipment to apply to our equipment to eliminate the possibility of future reverse connections.

column169: BETTER LOADING BY ORIGIN TERMINAL.  DRUMS AND/OR PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On the morning of January 22, 2008 I checked the roads at 06:00 and released the trucks because the roads were fine. Later that morning at approximately 08:50, mixed precipitation started falling, the roads froze in a matter of minutes. Our driver was entering a curve on Hwy 49 at the intersection of Hwy 62, another truck was in the ditch alongside the road and partially blocking the road. Our truck slid into the other truck and the bed of the other truck punctured the wall of our cargo tank on the back right seam between the head and the shell on the corner. The release was ongoing for approximately one hour. We attempted to plug the hole but were only able to slow the leak due to the location of the puncture. A&D Environmental was called and dispatched a vac truck and crew. The vac. truck immediately started recoiering product Bottom water dams were constructed below the highway and 800 tons of soil was removed. S&ME Environmental took samples of the area and of the water supply wells near the site. The samples were clean. I have include a copy of th NCSHP report that includes a diagram.
column169: I cannot see how we could have prevented this accident, I checked the roads befor releasing the truck and they were dry, and then froze in a matter of minutes. Perhaps we could have further delayed starting until well past sunrise.

column168: We received a cargo shipment on January 15, 2009 at LAX. It was processed and forwarded by air to PHL; the final destination for the shipment was Nigeria.There were problems confirming information on the shipment and we have been unable to contact the shipper. TSA,and Customs were advised, and TSA requested the shipment be opened for inspection. The shipment was opened on Jan. 28, 2009- local police, Customs and TSA used visual inspection as well as drug sniffing dogs to examine the shipment. The airway bill indicated that it contained used office and computer equipment. Upon inspection, the actual articles contained in the shipment were clothing and shoes (new with tags) as well as cosmetics. The cosmetic portion of the shipment included the following:• 7 gift box sets with an after shave balm, shower gel and Eau de toilet (3.4 oz, approximately 100 ml) in each.• Eau de Toilette - An alcohol/water based perfume solution containing 5 to 20 % aromatic compound.TSA and Customs are following up on the shipment.
